{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490949"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/780"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.02,0.64,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/780"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a two-day history of fever and right-sided abdominal pain. She has diet-controlled type II diabetes and is not on any medications. Her medical history includes several episodes of pyelonephritis. On examination, she appears unwell. Her blood pressure is 105/65 mmHg, pulse rate 100/min, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. There is tenderness and guarding in the right upper quadrant. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable. An ultrasound examination reveals a thick-walled gallbladder with a stone impacted in Hartmann\u0027s pouch (Image). She will be managed with bowel rest, intravenous fluids, analgesia, and intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following intravenous antibiotic regimens is most appropriate for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin","Metronidazole","Gentamicin","Amoxicillin, gentamicin, and metronidazole","Amoxicillin and gentamicin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has acute calculous cholecystitis, confirmed by the ultrasound finding of a thick-walled gallbladder with a stone impacted in Hartmann\u0027s pouch. The most common causative organisms are Gram-negative Enterobacteriaceae such as \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E, as well as Gram-positive \u003Cem\u003EEnterococcus faecalis\u003C/em\u003E. Empirical antibiotic therapy should therefore cover both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E together provide appropriate coverage for the likely pathogens in calculous cholecystitis. Amoxicillin covers many Gram-positive organisms, while gentamicin is effective against a broad range of Gram-negative bacteria, including Enterobacteriaceae. This combination is recommended for moderate calculous cholecystitis in otherwise stable patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not provide adequate coverage for Gram-negative organisms, which are the most common pathogens in this setting. Monotherapy may be considered only in mild cases or when other agents are contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is active against anaerobic bacteria but does not cover the typical aerobic Gram-negative or Gram-positive organisms responsible for calculous cholecystitis. It is not sufficient as monotherapy in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E alone provides Gram-negative coverage but lacks activity against Gram-positive organisms such as \u003Cem\u003EEnterococcus faecalis\u003C/em\u003E. Monotherapy is therefore inadequate for empirical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin, gentamicin, and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is a triple therapy regimen that is generally reserved for acalculous cholecystitis, which is more likely to involve anaerobic organisms and a broader spectrum of pathogens, particularly in critically unwell or immunocompromised patients. In calculous cholecystitis, the addition of metronidazole is not routinely required unless there is suspicion of anaerobic infection or severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute calculous cholecystitis is most commonly caused by Gram-negative Enterobacteriaceae and Enterococcus faecalis.","Empirical antibiotic therapy for calculous cholecystitis should cover both Gram-negative and Gram-positive organisms.","A combination of amoxicillin and gentamicin is appropriate for moderate calculous cholecystitis, while triple therapy is reserved for acalculous cases."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook [Internet]. Adelaide: AMH; c2020. Metronidazole [cited 2022 Feb 17]; [about 3 screens] . Available from: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.salus.idm.oclc.org/chapters/anti-infectives/antibacterials/other-antibacterials/metronidazole","Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care (ACSQHC). AURA 2017: second Australian report on antimicrobial use and resistance in human health. Sydney: ACSQHC; 2017. Available from: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/antimicrobial-use-and-resistance-in-australia/resources-page/.","Markotic F, Grgic S, Poropat C, et al. Antibiotics for adults with acute cholecystitis or acute cholangitis or both. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2020; 2020(6). Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7388910/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14340"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20887"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14340"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8489d55d-09b9-4a7a-9ffd-3399b802cc1b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8489d55d-09b9-4a7a-9ffd-3399b802cc1b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20887"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YdqfUt5I0PZWn4pIM8Stk0ZnX7A8ul.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YdqfUt5I0PZWn4pIM8Stk0ZnX7A8ul.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T22:58:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T23:00:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"780"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},